Anonymous Fri 24 Aug 2018 02:37:52 No.17857763 Report
Quoted By: >>17857846 >>17858298 >>17861268
>>17857413
Read. Like, read a lot. Pick up all the novels you hated reading in high school and just read. If you want to, take notes and read different people's analysis on the characters in these books as well as their dialogue. I'm not a huge cyberpunk addict, but I wouldn't read Acid Rain purely because the delivery is just not good. The introduction was jarring to me and Anon's inability to receive enhancements is...just there. It feels like something you thrown on the MC just so he can be a bit more unique than the others without any good reason.

If you have the time, unironically take some classes. Creative writing, grammar 101 and whatnot. If you find taking a class embarassing, don't. Community colleges might offer some courses and you can attend workshops to learn what's objectively good writing and get some recommendations for books to research, but the most important reason for classes is just getting motivation. I can sit here and tell you how to learn all day, but if you don't force yourself and practice, you wont improve. Having obligations like a class can push you to do things instead of procrastinating on what you should do.

Greentext is a writing style that's easy to learn and write in, but you need to move onto prose if you want to improve and learn more writing techniques, especially considering the size of your stories. I would gladly read Acid Rain if you decided to rewrite it completely one day in prose and employ a more coherent style.

>>17857694
I didn't say hate, and fruitful discussion comes from taking the time to talk with the opposition despite your differences. If you can put aside your beliefs and instead try to understand each other, you gain much more than just sitting around in a bubble with like-minded people and never embracing outside ideas.

>>17857745

First things first, the intro line seems really forced. Trying to use a term like deja vu to relate to the context can be done, but just outright writing
>They say Deja vu is proof that you are where you're supposed to be.
makes it sound like I'm about to read an expository essay trying to lecture me as opposed to reading a story about a guy from another world questioning whether he belongs.

On that topic, I'm not well-versed enough in the BHA universe, but I was able to sort of understand how it works based of scraps of info other Anons talked about many threads back. However, if I didn't have that prior knowledge, I would have zero idea on what BHA is or why I should care about it. If the universe is different from ours, EXPLAIN, BUT YOU DON'T HAVE TO DUMP EXPOSITION. ESTABLISH SCENES THAT PROVIDE MEANINGFUL CHARACTER INTERACTION THAT ALSO HAPPENS TO GIVE SMALL DETAILS ABOUT THE WORLD.

A huge portion of the intro is just what could be considered as major character details just skimmed over as if they meant nothing. I felt like I was reading a story outline as opposed to, well, a story. In your dump, you established three points.

>Jack was brought into the world young
>Jack works for BHA
>Jack wants love

Each of the three points could be scenes spanning several pages of length. If the MC's special for being here as a child, SHOW WHAT IT WAS LIKE FOR HIM AS A CHILD. Establish scenes of Jack's early years and how he viewed the world, his inner feelings, and how his surroundings react to him, especially his surroundings. A lot of the intro is inner dialogue, but you just provided bare-bones details on what he really thought about his situation.

He was saved by "The Raider." Personal pet peeve, nicknames like "The [noun]" are extremely generic and don't really work well. AGAIN, DESCRIBE HOW HE WAS SAVED. YOU JUST TALKED ABOUT A LIFE-CHANGING EVENT AND IGNORED IT.

You have a lot to work on. Refer to >>17857276 for practicing

tl;dr Show, don't tell.
